metadata.name: Ichigo #110
metadata.description:
This generator is named 'Ichigo' (苺/ いちご), the Japanese word for 'strawberry'. 

Seeing each iteration from a suitable distance, small dots (to me, reminiscent of strawberry seeds) overlay different sequences of geometric repetitions, implying a sense of texture, grittiness and irregularity. 

By looking closer however, it becomes apparent to the viewer that the majority of the composition is in fact government by orderly elements, in this case grids of dots. 

This discovery invites the viewer to consider the output in front of them at different levels, near and far. At what point do you feel the dots begin to dissolve into a texture? When do you stop noticing the dots and instead begin to perceive the overall composition?

These questions are posed in a similar fashion as with meditation; at what point does something become something else? When does an in-breath become an out-breath and vice versa? 

Contemplation on simple questions like these can open a small portal into stillness and mindfulness by taking time to slowly observe our responses. 

23 palettes are included, each named after different areas of Tokyo. 

Press 'S' to download a full size 6000px x 6000px PNG output. 

As always, much gratitude and enjoy your piece.

metadata.name: Representation #52
metadata.description:
Explore the world of gender politics through vibrant circles.

Representation is an artwork/data visualization about the gender split in parliaments across the world. 

Each minted artwork gets assigned 6 countries from different regions. 1 country from the Pacific, 1 from Europe, 1 from Asia, 1 from the Americas, 1 from Sub-saharan Africa and 1 from the Middle East and North Africa.

Each circle in your artwork represents the gender split of the parliament(s) in one of those countries by using colors. The legend in the bottom right can be used to decipher which color means what.

This artwork was created using p5js.

The artwork adapts to different screen sizes and ratios, so I exploring it on various devices or resizing your browser window. 

Features:

- Circle Size: What size are the circles?
- Circle Distance: How far apart from each other are the circles?
- Circle Scatter: Are the circles scattered on the Y-axis?

twitter: @ada_ada_ada_art

metadata.name: Study of atom in analog, digital and A.I. #92
metadata.description:
Experimental generative collection that merges analog photography, AI, generative text, and algorithmic coding, by digging down into the essence and building blocks of the different artistic communication channels. 

This work engages with all aforementioned mediums in a joint manner, guided by a random process. It starts with a collection of analog photographs, shot on film and scanned that were later used as a training dataset in Generative Adversarial Network (GAN) training. This way, A.I. learns the main characteristics of film photography. In particular, it mimics its recognizable grain. Another type of pixel grain is added with the use of code and pixel shifting as well as digital manipulation. Finally, the last type of “grain” appears with the use of generative text where a different kind of A.I. was given a short description of the project and instructed to imagine the rest of the story. The fragmented and void of meaning parts of generative text are added to the images as one of the possible traits.

issuer.name: Study of atom in analog, digital and A.I.

metadata.name: Intertwined #21
metadata.description:
Intertwined began as a study of how to overlap randomized shapes at many intersection points while retaining consistency and physical accuracy. I initially envisioned vines growing on buildings, but over time Intertwined moved in a more abstract embroidery-like direction while retaining influences from that foundational concept.

Controls:
Key S: Save the output as a jpeg at the current resolution (only available once the piece has finished loading).
Key Arrow Up: Scale the resolution up by a multiple of 1080 pixels. There is no maximum. The current highest recommended scale-factor is 4x.
Key Arrow Down: Scale the resolution down by a multiple of 1080 pixels. 1080p is the minimum.
Key A: Skip the construction animation to show the final result immediately (please note that for pieces with a larger grid skipping the animation may cause a long pause).

Browser Support: Confirmed to work in Chrome Version 97.0.4692.71

metadata.name: La Invernada #11
metadata.description:
This project is about my mother's lifestyle. Her work is breeding and herding goats, cows and horses.
She lives a cyclical life marked by two major stages during her livestock year: "La Veranada" and "La Invernada". My last work was about "La Veranada", this work is about "La Invernada", I hope you enjoy it.
Time in the life of a criancero is cyclical. Everything comes and goes, and comes back and comes back. Nature, so present, so in connection with the man and woman who inhabit it, marks the times perhaps like no other place.
 The succession of the seasons, the weather, the buds and "La Invernada", the sowing, the pastures, the harvest and the snows.
"La Invernada" is the place during what we could call the long winter, that is, from April to November.
"La Invernada" is down in the plains, in the pampas, in accessible places, where it is easy to supply forage to the goats that calve between October and November.
The "Criancero" rides a horse every day and, accompanied by his dogs, goes to "watch" the goats. They distinguish them in the distance. Every day is the same and different at the same time. Caring for, watching over and keeping the goats healthy and safe.
"El puesto" is their home. In the stall they use the water from the river, which they draw with a water pump, for their hygiene. Water for consumption is brought in jerry cans from "Vertientes", located about 10 km away.
 The hens roam freely throughout the day, when night comes some go to sleep in the "gallinero" and others simply sleep on small plants.
As you can see, life here is simple, solitary and with a lot of work.
I want to thank all those who have taken the trouble to read the story. I hope you liked it.
You can find real photos and videos of "La Invernada" on my twitter profile.

Features:
10 Color Palettes.
10 types of Animal pen.
Various types of chickens.
14 types of herbs.
10 types of flowerpot.
4 types of trees.
7 types of rivers.
The barn has 4 sizes.
The moon has a very varied range of x and y positions.
6% chance of getting snowy weather in the piece.


Press "S" in live mode to save the 2600 x 3000 image.
Note that the algorithm may take some time to run.
Created by Fernando. NFT 2.0 license.

metadata.name: Udnē #590
metadata.description:
Udnē is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Performance in Code: Deciphering Value in Generative Art, Art Basel Miami Beach, 2022.

Udnē is a collection of asymmetric textural compositions. It's a search for creating harmonies and disharmonies by combining 3 colors with 3 unsynchronized mathematical equations. Udnē explores the beauty within triadic compositions while attempting to integrate two contrasting textures by forming instances of non-figurative scenes. The collection is a reflection of integrated and contrasting textures in micro and macro scale that we see in our everyday life environment.

You can press 's' in liveMode to save as 1000x1000px .png.

In liveMode, add '&density=7’ to the end of the URL to render at high resolution (7000x7000px). You can use 5, 7 or 10 for different resolutions. It will automatically download when the rendering is finished. 

Some compositions might take longer to render in low-performance computers. Please be patient and enjoy the process!

As a rare probability there is an intentionally kept glitch.

Made with p5js.
@distcollective, November 2022

metadata.name: The Woodcarver's apprentice #25
metadata.description:
A mix of aesthetics from the Ukiyo-e and Shin-hanga woodblock movements, with modern elements.  

ukiyo-e (浮世絵) = "pictures of the floating world", which peaked in the late 19th century. 
shin-hanga (新版画) = "new prints", from roughly the 1920-1950s. 

Some comparisons between the prints of the Japanese masters and gen-art: 

* The number of prints. Based on how well a piece was received, the publisher could decide to produce more copies, usually in batches of 200. Compare this to limiting the edition size on fx(hash). The initial prints would have sharp lines and accurately coloured areas. Very popular prints with thousands of impressions would slowly degrade the blocks, leaving final prints with worn-out linework and colours that weren't true to originals.  

* Woodblock prints were actually a collab between the artist, the wood carver, and the printer. In many cases only the artist and publisher were recognized on the final prints. It was usually the publisher who owned the woodblock, not the artist. Often the artist was considered a worker, contracted at the request of the publisher or patrons funding the project. Compare this to the NFT space, where ownership is carved onto the blockchain, and artists have freedom to create whatever they wish. 

* Copyminters.... Similar to the NFT world, fake publishers sprang up from time to time, who would reproduce famous prints. Enji Takamizawa was one such counterfeiter, who was able to skilfully produce woodblocks replicating originals down to the wood grain! 

* While fine-quality woodblock prints from the Edo era command huge auction prices today, they were in reality affordable art for the regular people of their time. NFTs are similar in this light, where we can enjoy pieces at home rather than say, visiting galleries or museums of unattainable art. 



Additional querystring params (use when viewing in a separate window) 

* fullsize=true (33 megapixel output) 
* colourcorrect=false 
* grain=false 
* border=false 



Licenses included in source. Relying on: 

* PIXIJS for drawing 
* JSTS for geometry functions 
* chromajs for colour functions 
* noise and gaussian helpers from p5js

metadata.name: Garden, Monoliths #28
metadata.description:
"Garden, Monoliths" is the result of an algorithm that started in April 2021. It was called "Grass.js".
Spring was blooming all around the house, taking over the stones and remnants of ancient battles that stood here. Inspiration was everywhere.
The initial goal was to use mathematical formulas for creating patterns inspired by the density of nature, that could be used by a pen plotter, so it kept focusing on outputting vector lines. This history and practice produced a graphical style based on line strokes, plus occasionally some transparent, filled shapes.
Each artwork will be either "Garden" or "Monolith", for they are variations of two existing designs from the workshop.

metadata.name: Polymorph #194
metadata.description:
A polymorph tessellation is an irregular tessellation of regular polygons.
As the main tessellation used in this Truchet pattern is a polymorph tessellation and as the design morphs from chaotic patterning to rigid order we decided it was an appropriate name.

Keyboard interaction:
r - redraw with randomised tiles and colours within the same palette, other variables constant.
c - redraw with only chaos tiles.
o - redraw with only ordered tiles.
m - redraw with mixed tiles.
b - remove border.
d - restore border.
1,2,3,4,7 - redraw at corresponding values x 1000.
All of the above redraw the artwork and so will take a few seconds to complete.
Tiling pattern feature "Hexagons, Squares and Triangles" behaves slightly differently to the others in response to the 'o' and 'c' keys.
Each palette contains 7 colours from which 5 are chosen for each rendering. These are re-chosen on randomisation so may change the feel of the artwork significantly.
